---
import Base from '../layouts/Base.astro';
import NowReadout from '../components/NowReadout.astro';
import { site } from '../data/site';

const story = [
  `I grew up in Karnataka, India. The first time I understood scale, it was as a
   number with my name next to it: rank 86 among two hundred thousand students in
   the state entrance exam. At NIT Karnataka I studied computer science and picked
   up the conviction that still drives me — the whole stack is knowable, from the
   transistor to the product.`,
  `By my final year I was doing research: a capsule-network architecture for
   segmenting retinal fluid that cut trainable parameters by half compared to
   U-Net. It was published in Springer's Medical & Biological Engineering &
   Computing, and it taught me that a good constraint — fewer parameters, less
   compute — is a better teacher than a big budget.`,
  `At Samsung R&D I spent a year and a half inside phone cameras. The Night Mode
   multiframe pipeline I helped architect — C++, Neon SIMD, GPU shared memory,
   quantized models on NPUs — runs on millions of Galaxy devices. Shipping to
   hardware is a different sport: latency is physics, and there is no patch
   Tuesday for a camera.`,
  `I moved to the US for a Master's at USC, spent a summer at Skyworks making
   TensorFlow Lite for Microcontrollers faster (and upstreaming the fixes), and
   in 2024 joined Apple in Austin. Today I build the retail platform behind every
   Apple Store on the planet — event-driven microservices on Kafka and Temporal,
   holding a 99.99% uptime bar.`,
  `The thread through all of it: I like working where software meets its limits —
   silicon, latency, scale. On my own time I place bets on what comes next, mostly
   on agents. I'm building toward founding something; the bets are how I find out
   what. This site is where I keep the record honest.`,
];
---

<Base
  title="About"
  description="The story of Darshan D Vishwanath — Karnataka to NIT-K to Samsung to USC to Apple, and what comes next."
>
  <div class="prose-page">
    <header class="page-head">
      <p class="meta">The person</p>
      <h1>About</h1>
    </header>

    <div class="prose">
      {story.map((p) => <p>{p}</p>)}
    </div>

    <section class="block">
      <h2 class="meta head">Now</h2>
      <NowReadout />
    </section>

    <section class="block">
      <h2 class="meta head">Contact</h2>
      <p>
        The fastest way is email: <a href={`mailto:${site.email}`}>{site.email}</a>.
        I'm also on
        {site.socials.map((s, i) => (
          <>
            <a href={s.url} rel="me noopener">{s.label}</a>{i < site.socials.length - 1 ? ' and ' : '.'}
          </>
        ))}
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="block">
      <h2 class="meta head">Colophon</h2>
      <p class="meta colophon-text">
        built by hand with astro · set in inter &amp; jetbrains mono · hosted on
        github pages · no trackers, no analytics, nothing watching you read
      </p>
    </section>
  </div>
</Base>

<style>
  .page-head {
    padding-block: clamp(3rem, 8vh, 5rem) 2rem;
  }
  .page-head h1 {
    font-size: clamp(2.2rem, 5vw, 3.2rem);
    margin: 0.4rem 0 0;
  }
  .block {
    margin-top: 3.2rem;
  }
  .block .head {
    color: var(--accent);
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }
  .colophon-text {
    text-transform: none;
    letter-spacing: 0.04em;
    line-height: 1.9;
  }
</style>
